Here's a simple HTML and CSS example for a horizontal navigation bar with "Home," "About," "Services," and "Contact" links. The active link is highlighted using a class.

HTML:

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Navigation Bar</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="styles.css">
</head>
<body>

  <nav class="navbar">
    <ul class="nav-links">
      <li><a href="#" class="active">Home</a></li>
      <li><a href="#">About</a></li>
      <li><a href="#">Services</a></li>
      <li><a href="#">Contact</a></li>
    </ul>
  </nav>

</body>
</html>

CSS (styles.css):

body {
  margin: 0;
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

.navbar {
  background-color: #333;
}

.nav-links {
  list-style: none;
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
  display: flex;
}

.nav-links li {
  margin: 0;
}

.nav-links a {
  display: block;
  color: white;
  padding: 14px 20px;
  text-decoration: none;
  transition: background-color 0.3s;
}

.nav-links a:hover {
  background-color: #575757;
}

.nav-links a.active {
  background-color: #04AA6D;
}

How it works:

The nav bar is styled to be horizontal using flex.

The active class highlights the current page.

On hover, links change background for interactivity.


Let me know if you'd like it to be responsive or include dropdowns.